@jamesmacrae7730  there is enough info

that is the force-impulse or impulse momentum formula. the f * t part is impulse and the mvf-mvi is the change in momentum because momentum is p = mv so mv final - mv initial is the change in momentum which is equal to the f * t impulse so impulse = momentum. it's basically derived from the newton's 2nd law of f = ma cuz acceleration is v/t and if u plug that in its f = mv/t then when you multiply both sides by t you get the impulse-momentum formula.

During the time of contact between the ball and the wall, the force that the wall applies to the ball changes. Between 0 seconds and 0.0075 seconds, the force applied by the wall gradually increases from zero (as the ball comes more and more in contact with the wall). At 0.0075 the force applied by the wall is at its maximum. Between 0.0075 and 0.015 seconds, the force applied by the wall gradually decreases (as the ball leaves the wall).

Since the force applied to the ball changes over time, calculating the average force is much easier. The force that you are referring to as "just FORCE", will be the instantaneous force applied at a specific time. Calculating the instantaneous force will require limits.
